Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1945 at 2:10 p.m., five U.S. Navy Avenger torpedo-bombers, part of Flight 19, took off from Ft. Lauderdale Naval Air Station in Florida for a routine training mission and disappeared inside the Bermuda Triangle. 

After completing their initial objective, the flight plan called for them to head east for 67 miles, then north for 73 miles, before returning to the base, totaling 120 miles. 

Two hours into the mission, the flight leader, an experienced pilot, reported compass failures and became disoriented. His instruments malfunctioned, and the other pilots experienced similar issues. Despite attempts to contact land-based radio stations, the squadron's location could not be determined. At 6:20 p.m., the flight leader sent a confused radio message suggesting that the planes may have to ditch due to fuel shortage. By then, radar had located Flight 19 north of the Bahamas, but the search was complicated by poor weather.

A search and rescue Mariner aircraft with a 13-man crew was dispatched at 7:27 p.m., but it disappeared shortly after takeoff. A tanker off the Florida coast reported seeing an explosion. Despite one of the largest air and sea searches in history, no trace of the planes or the crew members was ever found.

The disappearance of Flight 19 and the Mariner contributed to the legend of the Bermuda Triangle, a region in the Atlantic Ocean where ships and aircraft are said to mysteriously vanish.

Name: Peters, Scott H.
text:
Over the Thanksgiving break, I heard a lot of concern about the proposed 23-story tower in Pacific Beach. The developer found a parcel technically not covered by the coastal height limit and aggregated a number of density incentives from state law to add up to a very tall project.

I support building more housing in our existing neighborhoods. I‚Äôm a founding member of San Diego YIMBY (Yes in My Backyard) Democrats and the bipartisan YIMBY Caucus in Congress. Homelessness is high where rents are high, and rents are high where supply fails to meet demand. The cost of housing is the biggest impediment to the prosperity of the Golden State, and unless we lower costs, our teachers, police, firefighters, and our children won‚Äôt be able to live here. To lower costs, we need more homes.

Part of the solution is to build more housing on underused properties in our existing neighborhoods, including coastal neighborhoods like Pacific Beach. New housing can improve neighborhoods and make them more vibrant, walkable, and safe. It‚Äôs what I did as a City Councilmember when we added 138 units on La Jolla Boulevard as part of the redesign. The Seahaus project replaced a dilapidated motel with an attractive housing project now inhabited by customers of local businesses, children in local schools, and engaged neighbors. The developer also funded the construction of two of the five roundabouts. It wasn‚Äôt easy ‚Äì some neighbors even filed a petition for my recall from office. But in the end, we got more housing and a better neighborhood.

That‚Äôs not what we will get from the Pacific Beach proposal. Other home builders I‚Äôve spoken to worry that it will taint the reputation of all development and be a poster child for those who resist all new housing. I hope the Turquoise Street developer will reconsider the proposal and offer something in better keeping with the scale of the neighborhood. I also understand that this project will likely exceed the surrounding height limit. We can accommodate taller buildings on the major streets that can still fit in. A four or six or maybe even an eight-story building on that property could provide a good number of units, still enhance the neighborhood, and provide a path for future developments of the sort. But this project, in its 23-story form, is a mistake.

I've inquired with @usedgov regarding this issue, however, their ability to intervene is limited due to state law being more expansive, so we continue to urge our state and local government to do the right thing for these children. These families have had to deal with accommodations being cruelly stripped from their children, and now they are also burdened with finding their own provider in just two weeks time when there is already a shortage of qualified special education providers. This solution is unfair to families who want their children to receive the support they deserve, and I urge the city and state to stop playing games with our children's education before the learning loss caused by this bureaucratic nightmare becomes irreparable.

Name: Mace, Nancy
text:
As temperatures drop across the Lowcountry, several warming shelters have opened to provide safe and warm environments for those in need. Here are the available options:

Holy City Missions Winter Warming Shelter at Aldersgate United Methodist Church
North Charleston, SC
Located at 1444 Remount Road, this shelter operates from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m. Guests receive a hot meal, breakfast, and access to showers. Men, women, and children are welcome; however, pets are not permitted. Transportation is available via CARTA bus route 13; passengers should request the Aldersgate Winter Warming Shelter stop.¬†
Seacoast Church Summerville Warming Center
Summerville, SC
Situated at 301 E. 5th North Street, with the entrance at the back door facing Gum Street, this center operates from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m. on designated nights. Guests are provided with a cot, warm dinner, to-go breakfast, and access to hot showers. While all are welcome, pets are not allowed. For transportation, CARTA buses have added a special stop on nights the center is open. Passengers should inform the driver if they need transport from the Charleston area to Summerville, as a transfer at Trident Hospital may be required.¬†

Hibben Hospitality Shelter
Mount Pleasant, SC
This shelter operates from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m. on designated nights, providing guests with a hot meal, breakfast, showers, and a change of clothes. Men, women, and children are welcome; pets are not allowed. Transportation details can be obtained by contacting local services.¬†

Goose Creek United Methodist Church Warming Center
Goose Creek, SC
Open from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m. on designated nights, this center offers a warm place to stay and meals. Men, women, and children are welcome; pets are not permitted. CARTA provides transportation to this location; passengers should check the latest schedules and stops.¬†

For the most current information on shelter availability and operating hours, it's recommended to contact the shelters directly or consult local authorities. Transportation assistance is available through CARTA bus services, with specific routes and stops designated for each shelter. Passengers should inform drivers of their intended destination to ensure proper routing.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
First, just how prevalent is telework in Washington?

‚ùóÔ∏è90% of bureaucrats telework
‚ùóÔ∏è6% of bureaucrats show up 5 days a week
‚ùóÔ∏èNearly 33% of employees are entirely remote
¬†
Why is this a problem?

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Well, these individuals have been caught doing just about everything during the workday except working.
¬†
My investigations have exposed bureaucrats playing golf, sitting in jail, relaxing in a bubble bath, and taking extended beach vacations.
¬†
All while on the clock. https://t.co/zuPGrcVriO

Name: Ernst, Joni
text: It would almost be funny, if it wasn‚Äôt happening on the taxpayers‚Äô dime and at the expense of veterans, seniors, small business owners, and Americans in need of competent service from government agencies.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Because bureaucrats do everything but work, not a single agency HQ in D.C. is even 50% full.
¬†
Average occupancy is just 12%. 

But taxpayers still foot the bill.

These empty buildings cost more than $8 billion every year to lease and $7.7 billion to maintain. https://t.co/bhmVMaPKcT

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
If that wasn't bad enough, 23-80% of surveyed teleworking bureaucrats are boosting their salaries by receiving incorrect locality pay.
¬†
What does this mean?

Name: Ernst, Joni
text: Bureaucrats decided they would move to areas with lower pay rates, some as far as 2,000 miles from their office, but still claim to be in their original location to incorrectly receive a higher paycheck.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text: So, how can we fix this and get Washington to work for Americans?

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
First, drain the swamp and relocate federal employees.

Moving those making the rules closer to those who live under them will benefit all Americans.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Third, track individual productivity because it is a privilege to telework.
¬†
We can evaluate performance and work product, just like the private sector does, and identify poor employees.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Second, downsize the federal government by implementing a "use it or lose it" approach.
¬†
If the government isn't using office space, let the leases expire, auction off the buildings, and consolidate the rest.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Lastly, and perhaps most important.

If bureaucrats don't want to return to work, I will happily make their dreams come true.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1240, the eight-day Siege of Kiev ends, resulting in a Mongol victory. 

The Mongols' assault, including the use of catapults, breached Kiev‚Äôs walls on the final day of the siege. As a result, the city's defenders suffered heavy losses, and many civilians were killed, particularly when the Church of the Tithes collapsed. By the end of the siege, Kiev was devastated. Most of the population was massacred, and much of the city was burned. Of the 50,000 inhabitants, only around 2,000 survived.

The victory marked a significant blow to the Principality of Galicia‚ÄìVolhynia, a medieval state in Eastern Europe known for its economic development and political power. The state was forced to submit to Mongol suzerainty, enabling the Mongols to continue their westward advance into Central Europe, specifically Hungary and Poland.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

LaTonya Andrews-Hunter is a proud Warren County resident, entrepreneur, and community advocate. She is a fourth-generation farmer and co-owner of Peanut & Zelb‚Äôs Produce Market in Norlina. An Air Force veteran and 27-year public health professional, LaTonya has dedicated her life to addressing food insecurity and improving access to healthy food in underserved communities.

Since moving to Warren County, she has expanded her impact by opening Peanut & Zelb‚Äôs, a year-round market that supports local farmers and provides fresh produce to the community. She also collaborates with local nonprofits, faith-based organizations, and rural health initiatives to deliver over 600 healthy food boxes monthly to residents of Warren and Halifax counties. She also partners with organizations like Pink with a Passion to educate breast cancer survivors on food and nutrition. 

LaTonya exemplifies leadership, resilience, and the power of giving back through her unwavering commitment. We are glad to shine the spotlight on her. 

#FridaySpotlight

text:
Chloe Cole‚Äôs story is gut-wrenching, but it‚Äôs one everyone needs to hear.

At 12 years old, she told her parents she was a boy. They took her to therapists and doctors, hoping for guidance. Instead, every single one of them pushed the Left‚Äôs gender ideology. They didn‚Äôt ask questions, didn‚Äôt explore other causes of her distress‚Äîthey just told her parents she *had* to transition or else she‚Äôd take her own life. By 13, she was on puberty blockers and testosterone. At 15, they removed her breasts. By 16, she realized it was all a terrible mistake.

And now, her story is more relevant than ever. The Supreme Court is reviewing Tennessee‚Äôs ban on gender transition treatments for minors‚Äîa case that could set a national precedent.

Chloe‚Äôs courage to speak out is saving lives, exposing an industry profiting off kids while ignoring lifelong consequences.

Share her story. Follow the case. The lives and futures of countless children depend on it.

@ChoooCole

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate the remarkable stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district, individuals who go above and beyond the ordinary. Today, we shine a spotlight on a man whose life has been defined by an unwavering commitment to service‚Äîmeet this week's Hometown Hero, Merle Winslow of Bristol Borough. 
 
A lifelong Bristol Borough resident, Merle‚Äôs legacy of service began in 1964 when he joined the Bristol Consolidated Fire Company upon graduating from Bristol High School. He then answered the call to serve his country, enlisting in the United States Army in 1965. Stationed in Germany as a Morse Code Radio Operator, his leadership and discipline quickly set him apart, earning him a promotion to Sergeant E5 in under two years‚Äîa testament to his character and resolve.
 
Upon returning home, Merle continued to answer the call to serve, this time as the Bristol Borough Fire Inspector. By 1969, he was appointed Fire Marshal, working tirelessly for nearly a decade to protect Bristol families and businesses. In 1995, Merle took on the role of Deputy Emergency Management Coordinator, and then, in 2003, stepped into the position of Emergency Management Coordinator‚Äîwhere he has served with unwavering commitment for the past 21 years. Throughout countless emergencies, Merle has been a steady, reliable leader, consistently guiding the community through crises with courage and expertise. His leadership has saved countless lives, prevented disasters, and ensured the safety of historic Bristol Borough.
 
Perhaps most inspiring is Merle‚Äôs enduring role as a volunteer firefighter. For an incredible 60 years, he has answered the call, running toward danger to protect others‚Äîa selfless commitment made even more remarkable when you consider he accomplished this alongside his demanding role as Emergency Management Coordinator.
 
Merle's lifetime of service and leadership have shaped a safer, stronger community, setting a standard for public service, and his kindness and spirit of generosity have earned him a place in the hearts of all who know him and the Bristol Borough history books. 
 
Please join me in thanking Merle for his decades of extraordinary service and wishing him a well-deserved retirement filled with happiness, joy, and the knowledge that his contributions have made an indelible impact on our community.

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text:
In January, Cole William Schmidtknecht went to the pharmacy to refill his asthma medication, which he had taken for years. At the pharmacy, Cole found out that the Pharmacy Benefit Manager had increased the price of Cole‚Äôs steroid prescription from around $35 dollars to over $500 dollars. He was told that no generic drug would be covered by his insurance, and Cole was forced to choose between paying for his medication, or for his rent. He chose to pay his rent. Five days later, Cole suffered a severe asthma attack that led to cardiac arrest and his untimely death.

This week, Cole's father joined me in Washington to honor his memory and to call on Congress to pass my Pharmacists Fight Back Act, which aims to end the price-gouging practices of PBMs and prevent tragedies like Cole‚Äôs from happening again.

Tensions between the U.S. and Japan had been escalating for years due to Japan's military expansion in Asia, particularly its invasion of China. By 1941, the U.S. had cut off vital exports to Japan, including oil, and severed diplomatic relations, leading Japan to consider war.

Japan‚Äôs military leaders planned the attack on Pearl Harbor as a means to cripple the U.S. Pacific Fleet and secure unchallenged control over Southeast Asia. Despite warnings of possible Japanese aggression, U.S. military leaders did not take sufficient precautions. Tensions in Washington were high, but key warnings failed to reach Pearl Harbor in time.

The attack began at 7:55 AM with a wave of bombers, torpedo planes, and fighters targeting the U.S. fleet. The Japanese destroyed or damaged eight battleships, three cruisers, and nearly 200 aircraft, killing over 2,300 Americans. However, the U.S. aircraft carriers were not in port and survived the attack, which later proved crucial in the Pacific war.

The attack unified the U.S. public, and Congress declared war on Japan the next day with only one dissenting vote. Japan‚Äôs miscalculation led to its eventual defeat in the war. Despite the severe damage at Pearl Harbor, the U.S. was able to recover quickly, and Japan‚Äôs strategy ultimately backfired, propelling the U.S. into a total war effort that would contribute to the Allied victory but at the cost of 400,000 American lives.

Name: Palmer, Gary J.
text:
Today marks the 83rd anniversary of the attack on Pearl Harbor.

Dozens of Alabamians were killed on this tragic day, including 32 on the USS Arizona and Julius Ellsberry, who was believed to be the first Black Alabamian to die in World War II.

Today, we honor the memory of all these brave Alabamians, but I would like to specifically focus on Chief Carpenter John Arnold Austin from Warrior, Alabama.

On the morning of December 7th, John was on board the USS Oklahoma, which was the first ship to be attacked by the Japanese on Battleship Row. John and many of his shipmates found themselves trapped, but he found an escape route and is credited with saving 15 sailors that day. Unfortunately, he perished in the process.

Chief Carpenter Austin was awarded the Navy Cross posthumously. His citation reads, "He gallantly gave his life in the service of his country." The USS Austin, a destroyer escort, was later named in his honor.

As we honor those lost, let us remember and reflect on their sacrifices and the high cost required to preserve freedom.

Name: Mills, Cory
text:
I am proud to co-sponsor H.R. 1492, the CBO Show Your Work Act, because voters deserve to know how their tax dollars are spent and how policies impacting their lives are decided. This legislation is a critical step toward greater transparency and accountability in the legislative process.

H.R. 1492 requires the Congressional Budget Office (CBO) to share the fiscal and policy models used to estimate the costs and economic impacts of proposed legislation. These estimates are foundational to shaping policy, from healthcare initiatives to tax reforms, and the American people must have access to see how these decisions are made.

Thank you @Rep_Davidson (OH-08), for leading this important piece of legislation.

Name: McCormick, Richard
text:
Pearl Harbor was not just an attack; it was a pivotal moment in our nation's history that galvanized a generation to defend our freedom and uphold the values we hold dear.

On that fateful day, the surprise assault by Japanese forces led to the loss of over 2,400 American lives and left a lasting scar on our nation. It reminds us of the sacrifices made by our brave men and women and the resilience of this country. The bravery displayed by our heroes during and after this tragedy is a testament to our collective strength.

As we reflect on Pearl Harbor and honor those who served and continue to serve our great nation, we must also remember the importance of having the strongest national defense at the ready. I look forward to reestablishing Peace through Strength come January.

#PearlHarborRemembranceDay  #NeverForget

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text:
Pharmacy benefit managers (PBMs) performed a useful function when they were formed last century. They managed formularies and payments, and they pushed back on drugmakers. But, then PBMs got greedy. Sitting in the middle of a complicated and opaque supply chain, they realized they could extract rents, profiting off higher drug prices that they passed onto patients and taxpayers. 

I joined @RepBuddyCarter's bipartisan PBM press conference to advocate for the lame-duck Congress to end rebates (a polite term for kickbacks) in Medicare and to begin demanding transparency and benchmarked pricing. My bipartisan bill, Pharmacists Fight Back, would go even further in reforms to help patients, pharmacists, and taxpayers, and has already secured more than 50 co-sponsors.

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
I appreciate the air strikes against ISIS targets in Syria, but it will not be enough. We have to ensure that the roughly 50,000 ISIS prisoners in northeastern Syria ‚Äî being primarily held by Kurdish forces ‚Äî are not released. 

We should not allow the Kurdish forces ‚Äî who helped us destroy ISIS on President Trump‚Äôs watch ‚Äî to be threatened by Turkey or the radical Islamists who have taken over Syria. 

Turkey has legitimate concerns regarding different groups that reside in northeastern Syria. But if there is conflict between Turkey and the Syrian Democratic Forces or Turkey attacks Kurdish forces, it will set in motion an ISIS jailbreak, which would be a nightmare for America. 

The last time ISIS was in charge, thousands of Europeans and Americans were killed by ISIS plots that originated in Syria. 

Furthermore, the reemergence of ISIS creates chaos throughout the region, which is going to lead to higher gas prices for us at home. 

Turkey deserves to have a demilitarized buffer zone between northeastern Syria and Turkey to protect Turkish interests. However, if Turkey takes military action against Kurdish forces in Syria, it will jeopardize America‚Äôs interests dramatically. 

In the past I have drafted sanctions targeting Turkey if they engage in military operations against the Kurdish forces who helped President Trump destroy ISIS. I stand ready to do this again in a bipartisan way.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1835, the Texan Army captured San Antonio, securing a significant victory for the Republic of Texas in its struggle for independence from Mexico.

The battle was part of a broader conflict that began when American settlers in Texas, then a Mexican territory, rebelled against Mexico's centralist government, which had replaced the republican constitution with a dictatorship under General Antonio L√≥pez de Santa Anna. 

The Texans, seeking independence, launched a series of skirmishes against Mexican forces. Soon after, Texan Army set its sights on San Antonio. In a four-day siege, they faced off against a well-entrenched Mexican force. The Mexican defenders surrendered, however, giving the Texans control of San Antonio. This victory solidified the momentum of the Texan revolution.

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
I had a very positive, thorough and candid meeting with Pete Hegseth about his nomination to be the next Secretary of Defense. I appreciated how forthright and forthcoming he was.

I have known Pete for many years, and I am familiar with his service in Afghanistan, as I was doing my reserve duty at the same time. Everyone in his unit in Afghanistan ‚Äì including our Afghan partners ‚Äì had nothing but great things to say about Pete. He is smart, passionate, and loves our men and women in uniform and our country.

The accusations being made regarding financial management of veterans service organizations and personal misconduct should only be considered by the committee if they are supported by testimony before Congress ‚Äì not anonymous sources.

When it comes to supporting presidential cabinet nominees, I have a record of being supportive regardless of party because I think every president deserves the right to pick their team.

The confirmation process for all nominees does and should allow for challenging questions, and I expect that to be the case here. However, I told Pete that he will be given the opportunity to defend himself and that his confirmation hearing should not be allowed to become a three-ring circus.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
 December 9, 2024
Congressman Jonathan L. Jackson Decries Acquittal of Daniel Penny in Jordan Neely‚Äôs Death

‚ÄúIs this who we are? Is this the new normal?‚Äù Congressman Jackson Urges Action to Restore the Sanctity of Life and Justice for Black Lives

Washington, D.C. ‚Äî Congressman Jonathan L. Jackson issued a powerful statement today in response to the acquittal of Daniel Penny, who faced charges related to the death of Jordan Neely, a young Black man experiencing a mental health crisis on a New York City subway.

‚ÄúThe outcome of this trial forces us to confront troubling questions about the society we are becoming. Is this who we are? Are we willing to accept a new normal where vigilantes feel entitled to take justice into their own hands, especially when it comes to Black lives?

Jordan Neely‚Äôs story is a heartbreaking reminder of the challenges faced by individuals living with mental health struggles. He deserved compassion, care, and assistance‚Äînot a violent end. The decision to acquit Daniel Penny sends a dangerous signal: that some lives, particularly Black lives, can be devalued without consequence.

This verdict mirrors systemic disparities we‚Äôve seen time and again. Consider how frequently Black men are subjected to harsh penalties for less severe actions. Cases like Albert Wilson and Kalief Browder underscore the glaring inequities in our justice system. Meanwhile, individuals like Penny, who take lethal action, are absolved. We must ask ourselves how we reconcile these outcomes with our claims of justice and equality.‚Äù
‚ÄúAmerica has always been a nation that wrestles with its conscience. Today, I urge us all to rise above fear and indifference, to embrace our better angels, and to reaffirm the value of every human life.

The killing of Jordan Neely should never have happened. It speaks to a failure on many levels: a failure of compassion, a failure of public systems to provide adequate mental health support, and a failure of the justice system to ensure accountability.

No one struggling with a mental health crisis should face violence instead of help. No Black life should be so easily disregarded. As a nation, we must reckon with this and commit to charting a different course.‚Äù

‚ÄúThis tragic case highlights urgent areas for action. As members of Congress, it is our responsibility to address the underlying issues that allow these injustices to persist.
1. Increase Oversight on the Use of Force:
Pass legislation that establishes      stricter standards for holding individuals accountable when they use      lethal force outside the boundaries of the law.
2. Improve Mental Health Support Systems:
Expand funding for crisis      intervention programs and mental health resources, particularly for      underserved communities.

Prioritize the passage of the Mental      Health Equity Act, which aims to address mental health disparities in      communities of color.

3. Curtail Vigilantism:
Strengthen federal penalties for      individuals who engage in extrajudicial violence, ensuring that no one      takes the law into their own hands without consequences.

4. Reform the Justice System:
Support legislation like the George      Floyd Justice in Policing Act to address racial bias and inequity in      the legal process.

5. Promote Community-Based Solutions:
Increase investments in programs      that provide non-violent responses to mental health crises, including      mobile crisis response units and peer support networks.‚Äù

6. Address Veterans‚Äô Mental Health Needs:
Adding complexity to this tragedy is Daniel Penny‚Äôs status as a military veteran. Veterans are among our nation‚Äôs most respected citizens, yet too often they face severe challenges, including mental health crises that go unaddressed. Congress must take proactive steps to ensure that veterans receive comprehensive mental health support. It is imperative to provide the necessary resources to prevent any veteran from contributing to or being caught in such devastating situations. The tragic loss of Jordan Neely is a reminder of Congress's responsibility to protect its citizens, invest in mental health services, and reform judicial inequities.

To this end, legislators like Congressmen David Trone and Ro Khanna have sponsored critical measures to address mental health needs, including:

The Occupational Therapy Mental      Health Parity Act, which enhances access to occupational therapy for mental health      under Medicare, ensuring veterans and others can access holistic,      life-improving services.
H.R. 2067, the Medication Access and      Training Expansion (MATE) Act, designed to improve training for      treating substance use disorders, which are closely tied to mental health      issues.

These legislative efforts emphasize the need for targeted support systems for veterans, addressing underlying issues such as PTSD, anxiety, and societal reintegration challenges.

Advocate for national standards      in crisis response, ensuring trained professionals‚Äînot civilians‚Äîintervene      in mental health emergencies.

Expand funding for community      mental health programs and veterans' mental health services to prevent      tragedies like this.

Congress must increase funding      for veterans‚Äô mental health services through the Department of Veterans      Affairs (VA), including therapy, counseling, and crisis intervention.

Support legislation that expands      training for veterans transitioning to civilian life, focusing on      de-escalation and understanding mental health crises in the community.

By addressing veterans‚Äô mental health needs comprehensively, we can ensure that our heroes receive the care they deserve while also helping to prevent situations where unresolved trauma may lead to tragedy.

‚ÄúThe acquittal of Daniel Penny is not just a failure of the courts‚Äîit is a failure of our collective humanity. This moment calls on all of us to reflect and act. Allowing tragedies like this to become the norm is unacceptable.
The time has come to renew our commitment to protecting the vulnerable, ensuring justice for the marginalized, and reaffirming the inherent dignity of every person.
Jordan Neely‚Äôs life mattered. Black lives matter. And as a nation, we must do better to honor that truth.‚Äù

The Biden-Harris administration‚Äôs eleventh-hour lease sale in ANWR is yet another charade aimed at subverting the will of Congress in the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act. 

The Biden Interior Department is proposing a lease sale that closes three-quarters of the 1002 Area‚Äîincluding lands that are projected to have substantial resources beneath them‚Äîafter having previously cancelled all of the leases lawfully-issued under the first statutorily mandated lease sale. 

But the most insulting aspect of BLM‚Äôs announcement today is the agency‚Äôs claim to have ‚Äòconsulted with Alaska Native Tribes and Corporations‚Äô on this Record of Decision. Having spoken with the leaders of these entities, I can report that nothing is further from the truth. The Biden-Harris administration has never given any weight to the voices of the Alaska Native people in the region who strongly support responsible resource development in ANWR for the benefit of their communities‚Äîjust like the Biden-Harris administration refused to even meet with Alaska Native leaders when promulgating their illegal NPR-A rule. Cancelling Alaska Native voices continues under the Biden-Harris administration, but don‚Äôt hold your breath for the mainstream media to write that story. 

The good news is we will soon be working with the Trump administration which, unlike Biden-Harris, has a proven track record of responsible oil and gas production and Alaska resource development, and respects the voices of the I√±upiat people of the North Slope.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1936, Edward VIII signs the instrument of abdication to marry American socialite Wallis Simpson. 

A constitutional crisis emerged in the British Empire when King Edward VIII announced his intention to marry Wallis Simpson, an American divorc√©e. This proposal faced strong opposition from the British government and the Commonwealth due to religious, legal, and moral objections. As the head of the Church of England, Edward's potential marriage to a twice-divorced woman was deemed unacceptable, as the church did not permit remarriage if the former spouse was still alive. 

Despite the objections, Edward remained determined to marry Simpson, whom he claimed to love. His refusal to give her up led to his abdication, and he was succeeded by his brother, Albert, who became George VI. Edward was given the title Duke of Windsor and married Simpson the following year. They remained married until his death 35 years later.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
Today, we honor the life and legacy of the incomparable #NikkiGiovanni, a poet, activist, and truth-teller whose words moved nations and inspired generations.

Through powerful works like "Ego-Tripping", "Cotton Candy on a Rainy Day", and "Love Poems", Nikki captured the struggles and triumphs of the Black experience with unmatched eloquence. Her collections, including "Black Feeling, Black Talk" and "Re: Creation", were not just poetry‚Äîthey were calls to action during the #CivilRightsMovement, giving voice to the fight for equality and justice.

Nikki Giovanni reminded us that poetry is power, that art can heal, and that words can build movements. Her unwavering commitment to social justice and her celebration of Black culture taught us to resist oppression and embrace our humanity.

Rest in power, Nikki. Your brilliance, courage, and love for our people will continue to guide us forward.

#NikkiGiovanni  #RestInPower

text:
BIG WIN FOR PINELLAS!

We just secured VITAL authorization to restore our dunes and renourish beaches in Long Key, Sand Key, and Treasure Island. The 2024 WRDA will protect our homes, businesses, wildlife, and infrastructure, making them more resilient and safer during hurricanes, storms, and floods while ensuring tourism continues to thrive in our district.

These provisions include ongoing maintenance over the next two years, saving lives and tens of millions of dollars in hurricane damage relief costs for federal and local governments every year.

We also cut through red tape, requiring the Secretary of the Army to work directly with local authorities to streamline processes and ensure these critical projects move forward smoothly.

But the fight doesn‚Äôt stop here. This is just the beginning. I‚Äôm committed to continuing the work needed to fully address these challenges and protect Pinellas for future generations. This is the first step toward a stronger, safer future for our district.

Making Pinellas Great Again!
